    49	\begin{document}
    50	\maketitle
    51	
    52	\begin{abstract}
    53	Preprocessing screening is often the most expensive part of a near-infrared
    54	spectroscopy calibration workflow.  It works because smoothing, derivatives,
    55	detrending and related filters change the spectral directions seen by PLS or
    56	Ridge regression, but a full external search repeatedly refits nearly the same
    57	linear model.  This paper studies the case where that search can be collapsed
    58	into one calibration step.
    59	
    60	For strict linear preprocessing operators, the transformed PLS
    61	cross-covariance satisfies
    62	$(\X\A\transpose)\transpose\Y=\A\X\transpose\Y$, and Ridge regression
    63	depends on the operator-induced kernel
    64	$\X\A\transpose\A\X\transpose$.  These identities allow a finite operator
    65	bank to be screened inside the model while retaining original-wavelength
    66	coefficients.  Sample-adaptive or fitted corrections such as SNV, MSC, EMSC
    67	and ASLS remain fold-local branches, not absorbed into the algebra.
    68	
    69	The study uses the AOM benchmark cohort: 61 regression rows in the manifest
    70	and 17 classification rows.  On the main regression denominator ($N=32$),
    71	plain compact-bank AOM-PLS records median RMSEP ratios of 0.991 against
    72	PLS-default and 0.990 against PLS-HPO; the selected
    73	\texttt{ASLS-AOM-compact-cv5} branch records 0.985 and 1.002 on the same two
    74	references.  The plain \texttt{AOMRidge-global-compact-none} baseline records
    75	0.974 against Ridge-default and 0.984 against Ridge-HPO, while the selected
    76	\texttt{AOMRidge-Blender-headline-spxy3} records 0.918 and 0.966.  The
    77	selected classifier, \texttt{AOM-PLS-DA-global-simpls-covariance}, improves
    78	balanced accuracy by 0.159 on $N=13$ datasets with 12/13 wins.  The runtime
    79	gap is the practical result: PLS-HPO takes a median total time of 710.81 s per
    80	run, whereas the selected AOM-PLS branch takes 1.63 s.  Linear
    81	operator-adaptive calibration therefore gives comparable prediction quality to
    82	exhaustive preprocessing screening, with orders-of-magnitude less fitting
    83	time for PLS.
    84	\end{abstract}
    85	
    86	\noindent\textbf{Keywords:} near-infrared spectroscopy; chemometrics;
    87	preprocessing selection; partial least squares; ridge regression; operator
    88	kernels; calibration.
    89	
    90	\section{Introduction}
    91	
    92	Near-infrared spectroscopy (NIRS) is used because it is rapid,
    93	non-destructive and compatible with routine analytical deployment
    94	\citep{burns2007handbook,pasquini2018near}.  The calibration step is still
    95	fragile.  A model that works on raw spectra may fail after a different split,
    96	instrument or sample family, while the same regressor with a derivative,
    97	smoother or baseline correction can become usable.  In practice, much of the
    98	model-building effort is therefore spent screening preprocessing choices.
    99	
   100	The usual response is external search.  A calibration workflow enumerates
   101	normalizations, smoothers, derivative orders, baseline corrections and model
   102	hyperparameters, then chooses the best validated pipeline.  That workflow is
   103	straightforward and often effective, but it is slow.  It also hides a
   104	scientific question inside a large engineering loop: which spectral linear
   105	geometry does the calibration model need?
   106	
   107	The cost is concrete in this benchmark.  The full PLS preprocessing grid
   108	evaluates 600 combinations across five trials, and the Ridge grid evaluates
   109	the same combinations across ten trials, giving 3000 and 6000 candidate fits
   110	per dataset/seed before the final refit.  Repeating this search on small
   111	calibration sets can also make the selected pipeline unstable: the chosen
   112	preprocessing is the winner of a multiplicative loop over folds, operators and
   113	model hyperparameters.  A single operator-adaptive linear fit is easier to
   114	audit because the selected geometry is part of one calibration object with
   115	coefficients recovered on the original wavelength axis.
   116	
   117	This paper focuses on the part of preprocessing that has a simple algebraic
   118	answer.  If a preprocessing step is a fixed linear operator on the wavelength
   119	axis, it can be represented by a matrix $\A$ and moved inside PLS or Ridge
   120	calibration.  The model can then screen a bank of such operators in one fit
   121	rather than refitting every transformed data matrix as an external pipeline.
   122	This does not claim that every preprocessing step is linear.  SNV, MSC, EMSC
   123	and ASLS are fitted or sample-adaptive transformations; they remain
   124	fold-local branches in the experimental protocol.
   125	
   126	The contribution is deliberately narrow.  We derive the PLS covariance
   127	identity and the Ridge operator-kernel identity, instantiate them in AOM-PLS
   128	and AOM-Ridge, and test the resulting models against default PLS/Ridge and
   129	full cartesian preprocessing-HPO baselines.  The question is not whether a
   130	new nonlinear learner can win a benchmark.  The question is whether the
   131	preprocessing search already used with linear chemometric models can be made
   132	faster, simpler and easier to audit.
   133	
   134	The key empirical check is intentionally plain.  The AOM-compact-cv5 PLS row
   135	and the AOMRidge-global-compact-none Ridge row use compact strict-linear banks
   136	without the selected ASLS branch, Blender selector or local-neighbourhood
   137	machinery.  If these simple AOM baselines already compete with default and
   138	preprocessing-HPO PLS/Ridge, the algebra is doing useful work rather than only
   139	moving complexity into another tuning grid.
   140	
