   151	\section{Related work}
   152	
   153	Spectral preprocessing is a central part of chemometrics.  Common tools
   154	include Savitzky--Golay smoothing and derivatives
   155	\citep{savitzky1964smoothing}, Norris--Williams derivatives
   156	\citep{norris1976influence}, SNV \citep{barnes1989standard}, MSC
   157	\citep{geladi1985linearization}, EMSC \citep{martens1991extended} and
   158	penalized baseline smoothers \citep{eilers2003perfect,zhang2010baseline}.
   159	Reviews emphasize that these transformations remove different nuisance
   160	structures and should be chosen with the analytical setting in mind
   161	\citep{rinnan2009review}.
   162	
   163	PLS remains the reference linear method for many NIRS calibration problems
   164	\citep{geladi1986partial,wold2001pls}.  NIPALS and SIMPLS offer two useful
   165	views: one iterative and score-based, the other covariance-based
   166	\citep{dejong1993simpls}.  Ridge regression provides a complementary
   167	regularized linear model \citep{hoerl1970ridge}; in dual form it depends on
   168	the sample Gram matrix, which makes preprocessing a change of kernel geometry
   169	\citep{scholkopf2002learning,hastie2009elements}.
   170	
   171	This work combines these two lines.  It keeps the chemometric interpretability
   172	of linear calibration, but treats strict preprocessing alternatives as
   173	operators that can be selected inside the model rather than as independent
   174	outer-loop pipelines.
   175	
   176	\section{Linear-operator scope}
   177	
   178	Let $\X\in\R^{n\times p}$ be a centered spectral matrix, with rows as samples
   179	and columns as wavelengths.  A strict linear preprocessing operator is a fixed
   180	matrix $\A\in\R^{p\times p}$ applied to each row spectrum:

exec
/bin/bash -lc "nl -ba paper_aom/main.tex | sed -n '181,360p'" in /home/delete/nirs4all/nirs4all
