   212	\section{Methods}
   213	
   214	\subsection{Covariance identity for one-shot AOM-PLS}
   215	
   216	For centered $\X$ and $\Y$, the transformed PLS cross-covariance for operator
   217	$\A_b$ is
   218	\begin{equation}
   219	  (\X\A_b\transpose)\transpose\Y
   220	  =
   221	  \A_b\X\transpose\Y .
   222	  \label{eq:cov_identity}
   223	\end{equation}
   224	Equation~\ref{eq:cov_identity} is the core simplification.  It means that a
   225	bank of strict linear preprocessings can be screened by acting on
   226	$\X\transpose\Y$, without fitting one full PLS model for every transformed
   227	matrix.
   228	
   229	The simulation check for this identity is direct: explicit transformed-space
   230	PLS and covariance-space AOM-PLS must select the same operator direction when
   231	the same centered fold and operator bank are supplied.  The check is used as
   232	an implementation guard, while the benchmark below evaluates the effect on
   233	held-out prediction.
   234	
   235	\subsection{AOM-PLS solvers and coefficient recovery}
   236	
   237	A standard PLS coefficient matrix can be written as
   238	\begin{equation}
   239	  \B=\mathbf W(\mathbf P\transpose\mathbf W)^+\mathbf Q\transpose ,
   240	\end{equation}
   241	where $\mathbf W$ are weights, $\mathbf P$ are spectral loadings,
   242	$\mathbf Q$ are response loadings and $+$ denotes the Moore--Penrose inverse.
   243	In AOM-PLS, a component may be selected in a transformed space.  If the
   244	transformed-space direction is $r_a$ under operator $\A_b$, its
   245	original-wavelength direction is
   246	\begin{equation}
   247	  z_a=\A_b\transpose r_a .
   248	\end{equation}
   249	With $\Z=[z_1,\ldots,z_k]$ and scores $\T=\X\Z$, the recovered coefficient
   250	matrix is
   251	\begin{equation}
   252	  \B=\Z(\mathbf P\transpose\Z)^+\mathbf Q\transpose .
   253	  \label{eq:aompls_coef}
   254	\end{equation}
   255	The fitted model is therefore still one linear calibration on the original
   256	wavelength grid.
   257	
   258	Two solver views are implemented.  The NIPALS-adjoint solver applies operator
   259	adjoints during iterative score extraction.  The SIMPLS-covariance solver
   260	uses Equation~\ref{eq:cov_identity} directly in covariance space.  The main
   261	plain baseline is \texttt{AOM-compact-cv5}: the compact nine-operator bank
   262	with internal five-fold selection and no fitted ASLS branch.  The selected
   263	regression result uses the same compact CV5 branch after ASLS is fitted
   264	fold-locally.  The default bank, SIMPLS-only variants, and other non-selected
   265	AOM variants are reported in the supplementary material.
   266	
   267	The compact bank was chosen from the selector diagnostics, not by adding an
   268	unbounded operator catalogue.  In the refreshed diagnostics, the three most
   269	frequent strict operators
   270	(\texttt{sg\_smooth\_w21\_p3}, \texttt{sg\_d1\_w21\_p3} and
   271	\texttt{sg\_d1\_w11\_p2}) account for 54.7\% of compact-bank component
   272	selections, while identity remains selected on 8.7\% of components.  The
   273	operator bank is therefore diverse enough to adapt, but small enough to keep
   274	the selection problem stable.
   275	
   276	\subsection{AOM-Ridge operator kernels}
   277	
   278	For centered spectra $\X_c$ and response $\Y_c$, Ridge regression can be
   279	solved in the dual.  Operator $\A_b$ induces the kernel
   280	\begin{equation}
   281	  \K_b=\X_c\A_b\transpose\A_b\X_c\transpose .
   282	  \label{eq:ridge_kernel}
   283	\end{equation}
   284	For regularization $\alpha>0$,
   285	\begin{equation}
   286	  \mathbf C=(\K_b+\alpha\mathbf I_n)^{-1}\Y_c,
   287	  \qquad
   288	  \bm\beta_b=\A_b\transpose\A_b\X_c\transpose\mathbf C .
   289	  \label{eq:ridge_beta}
   290	\end{equation}
   291	Weighted operator mixtures are obtained by replacing $\K_b$ with
   292	\begin{equation}
   293	  \K=\sum_b s_b^2\X_c\A_b\transpose\A_b\X_c\transpose,
   294	\end{equation}
   295	which gives an original-space coefficient matrix through the matching
   296	operator metric
   297	$\sum_b s_b^2\A_b\transpose\A_b$.
   298	
   299	The plain Ridge baseline is \texttt{AOMRidge-global-compact-none}: one global
   300	selection over the compact strict-linear bank, without Blender mixing or local
   301	neighbourhood routing.  The selected Ridge result uses the Blender selector
   302	(\texttt{AOMRidge-Blender-headline-spxy3}).  It combines several strong
   303	operator geometries through internal validation rather than committing to one
   304	noisy winner.  GCV, local-neighbourhood and additional global compact
   305	selectors are mathematically described in the supplement.
   306	
