   507	\subsection{Time budget}
   508	
   509	The practical advantage is runtime.  PLS-HPO has a median total time of
   510	710.81 s per run and an observed row total of 40.8 h.
   511	AOM-PLS (simple), implemented as \texttt{AOM-compact-cv5}, has a median total
   512	time of 1.18 s, and AOM-PLS (best) has a median total time of 1.63 s and an
   513	observed total of 0.1 h.  On median total time, AOM-PLS (best) is about 436
   514	times faster than PLS-HPO.  In runner-level search units, the contrast is
   515	3000 trial fits per PLS-HPO dataset/seed versus 45 compact-bank CV fits for
   516	each AOM-PLS row.
   517	
   518	Ridge is different because AOM-Ridge (best), the Blender selector, is heavier.
   519	It still improves over Ridge-HPO, and its median total time is 728.81 s
   520	compared with 1584.00 s for Ridge-HPO.  AOM-Ridge
   521	(simple), implemented as \texttt{AOMRidge-global-compact-none}, is much
   522	lighter, with median total time 23.78 s and 450 operator-alpha cells.  The
   523	result is not that every AOM selector is instant; it is that strict-linear
   524	preprocessing can be represented as a model geometry rather than as a blind
   525	external pipeline loop.
