    47	\section{Notation, Scope and Complete Derivations}
    48	
    49	\subsection{Strict linear operators}
    50	
    51	Let $\X\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times p}$ be a spectral matrix and
    52	$\Y\in\mathbb{R}^{n\times q}$ a response matrix.  A strict linear spectral
    53	operator $\A_b\in\mathbb{R}^{p\times p}$ acts on row spectra as
    54	\begin{equation}
    55	  \X_b=\X\A_b\transpose .
    56	\end{equation}
    57	The operator is fixed once the wavelength grid and hyperparameters are fixed.
    58	The compact bank contains identity, Savitzky--Golay smoothers and
    59	derivatives, finite differences and polynomial detrending projections.
    60	
    61	Sample-adaptive or fitted transformations do not satisfy this definition.
    62	SNV uses sample-specific statistics, MSC and EMSC estimate correction
    63	parameters relative to a reference, and ASLS solves an asymmetric baseline
    64	problem.  They are valid preprocessing branches, but they are fitted inside
    65	each calibration fold and are not inserted into the strict-linear operator
    66	identities.
    67	
    68	\subsection{AOM-PLS covariance identity}
    69	
    70	For centered $\X$ and $\Y$, standard PLS can be written with weights
    71	$\mathbf W$, loadings $\mathbf P$ and response loadings $\mathbf Q$:
    72	\begin{equation}
    73	  \B=\mathbf W(\mathbf P\transpose\mathbf W)^+\mathbf Q\transpose .
    74	\end{equation}
    75	For a fixed operator $\A_b$,
    76	\begin{equation}
    77	  (\X\A_b\transpose)\transpose\Y
    78	  =
    79	  \A_b\X\transpose\Y .
    80	  \label{eq:sup_cov_identity}
    81	\end{equation}
    82	Equation~\ref{eq:sup_cov_identity} is the algebraic reason why strict-linear
    83	preprocessing alternatives can be evaluated in covariance space.  The
    84	SIMPLS-covariance implementation acts on $\X\transpose\Y$ directly.  The
    85	NIPALS-adjoint implementation applies $\A_b$ and $\A_b\transpose$ during the
    86	iterative extraction without storing every transformed design matrix.
    87	
    88	If a transformed-space direction for component $a$ is $r_a$, the
    89	original-wavelength direction is
    90	\begin{equation}
    91	  z_a=\A_b\transpose r_a .
    92	\end{equation}
    93	With $\Z=[z_1,\ldots,z_k]$ and $\T=\X\Z$, the final coefficient matrix is
    94	\begin{equation}
    95	  \B=\Z(\mathbf P\transpose\Z)^+\mathbf Q\transpose .
    96	  \label{eq:sup_aompls_coef}
    97	\end{equation}
    98	Thus the fitted AOM-PLS object predicts from original spectra and can expose
    99	coefficients on the original wavelength grid.
   100	
   101	\subsection{AOM-Ridge kernels}
   102	
   103	For centered $\X_c$ and $\Y_c$, a single operator induces
   104	\begin{align}
   105	  \mathbf Z_b &= \X_c\A_b\transpose,\\
   106	  \K_b &= \mathbf Z_b\mathbf Z_b\transpose
   107	       = \X_c\A_b\transpose\A_b\X_c\transpose,\\
   108	  \mathbf C_b &= (\K_b+\alpha\mathbf I_n)^{-1}\Y_c,
   109	\end{align}
   110	and the recovered original-space coefficient matrix is
   111	\begin{equation}
   112	  \bm\beta_b=\A_b\transpose\A_b\X_c\transpose\mathbf C_b .
   113	\end{equation}
   114	For weighted operator mixtures,
   115	\begin{equation}
   116	  \K=\sum_{b=1}^{m}s_b^2\X_c\A_b\transpose\A_b\X_c\transpose,
   117	  \qquad
   118	  \mathbf M=\sum_{b=1}^{m}s_b^2\A_b\transpose\A_b,
   119	\end{equation}
   120	so
   121	\begin{equation}
   122	  \bm\beta=\mathbf M\X_c\transpose(\K+\alpha\mathbf I_n)^{-1}\Y_c.
   123	\end{equation}
   124	This is the Ridge counterpart of AOM-PLS: PLS adapts supervised
   125	cross-covariance directions, while Ridge adapts the regularized sample
   126	geometry.
   127	
   128	\subsection{Ridge selector family}
   129	
   130	The main manuscript now reports both the plain global compact selector and the
   131	Blender selector.  The full Ridge family also includes branch-specific compact
   132	variants, local-neighbourhood selectors and multi-branch kernel mixtures.
   133	Global selectors choose one operator geometry for the whole calibration set.
   134	Local selectors restrict the geometry to neighbourhoods such as $k=50$ nearest
   135	calibration samples.  Multi-branch kernels combine several branch geometries
   136	with shrinkage.  These variants are useful for understanding the design space,
   137	but their refreshed paired statistics do not beat Blender on the main Ridge
   138	denominators.
   139	
   140	\subsection{FastAOM derivation}
   141	
   142	FastAOM is treated here as an exploration of alternative AOM forms, not as a
   143	main result.  It defines a chain as an ordered composition of primitive
   144	strict operators.  The grammar assigns roles to operators:
   145	baseline/projection, smoothing, derivative and projection-mask operations.  A
   146	depth cap limits the number of composed operators, and grammar pruning removes
   147	invalid or redundant role sequences before screening.
   148	
   149	For each fold-local base $B_j(\X)$ and chain $s$, FastAOM computes
   150	\begin{equation}
   151	  \mathrm{score}(j,s)
   152	  =
   153	  \frac{\left\|A_s B_j(\X_c)\transpose y_c\right\|_2^2}
   154	       {\left\|B_j(\X_c)A_s\transpose\right\|_F^2
   155	        \left\|y_c\right\|_2^2}.
   156	\end{equation}
   157	With a truncated SVD $B_j(\X_c)\approx U_j\Sigma_jV_j\transpose$ and
   158	$F_{j,s}=A_sV_j\Sigma_j$, the screened kernel is approximated by
   159	\begin{equation}
   160	  \K_{j,s}
   161	  =
   162	  B_j(\X_c)A_s\transpose A_s B_j(\X_c)\transpose
   163	  \approx U_j C_{j,s}U_j\transpose,
   164	  \qquad
   165	  C_{j,s}=F_{j,s}\transpose F_{j,s}.
   166	\end{equation}
   167	
